           Aircraft Laser Infrared Absorption Spectrometer (ALIAS)

   Dr. Christopher R. Webster(PI), Gregory J. Flesch, Dr. David C. Scott,
            Dr. Robert L.Herman, Katy Modarress, James E. Swanson

   Consultants: Dr. Randy D. May (Spectrasensors) and W. Stephen Woodward

     Previous contributors:  Curtis A. Trimble, Robert G. Chave, Matthew
     A. Tuchscherer, James Kendall, Dr. Lyatt Jaegle, Dr. Hua Hu, Gwen
     Eknayan, Julie Jensen, Ronald Howe, George Mohler, Ted Brunzie,
     Alissa Fitzgerald, Scott Atkinson
              [alias.gif]    ER2RightPodinFlight2.jpg (34359 bytes)

   The Aircraft Laser Infrared Absorption Spectrometer (ALIAS) instrument
   is a high resolution four-channel scanning tunable diode laser
   spectrometer (3.4 to 8 µm) which makes direct, simultaneous
   measurements of HCl, NO[2], CH[4], N[2]O, and CO (including vertical
   profiles of the tracers) in the stratosphere and troposphere at
   sub-parts-per-billion sensitivities. The instrument weighs 155 lbs.

   The measurement technique is based upon using tunable lead-salt diode
   lasers operating from 3.4 to 8 µm scanning over absorption lines
   recorded using second harmonic absorption spectroscopy over an 80-m
   pathlength in a 1-m multipass optical cell of the Herriott design.
   ALIAS has flown over 250 times in 6 major NASA missions: AASE-II,
   SPADE, STRAT, ASHOE/MAESA, POLARIS, and SOLVE.

